g.text: EleanorRank5Convo7 begins.

g.title: j2187576717
g.text: Is ‘The Indifference’ what it IS, or what it WANTS?

g.title: j2465779904
g.text: You and Lettie both do that, you know. You forget to say "Hello."

g.title: j2759611058
g.text: Most people would start with "hello."

g.title: j5866127
g.text: [Ignore.]

g.title: j2285502693
g.text: You have found the one thing we share, congratulations. And sorry. This is more important.

g.title: j686084793
g.text: Sorry. This is more important.

g.title: Chat ends.
g.text: Chat ends.

g.title: j114352714
g.text: I think ‘The Great Indifference’ is going to try to get between us, somehow.

g.title: j4260257902
g.text: Don’t laugh. I can feel it, deep down in my bone marrow. The thing that was in Rusalka would love to see us tearing each other into pieces.

g.title: j968060828
g.text: I don’t know why. I just know.

g.title: j2313879477
g.text: Yeah. I think you’re right.

g.title: j2503339693
g.text: Maybe that’s what happened to Entrati’s family. They’ve been living right on top of his lab for years, without knowing it. When the kid found them, they were estranged, wallowing in spite.

g.title: j3285032294
g.text: I’ve seen it in your head. Albrecht and Loid. Mother and Father. You and your parents. Rusalka and Viktor, for all we know. And the six of us, of course.

g.title: j1675775482
g.text: What this thing does is cold. Perverse. But there’s a motivation behind it, somewhere.

g.title: j2425182624
g.text: I think you’re right. On the Zariman, the parents were the first to lose their minds. Maybe the Holdfasts held out as long as they did because none of them had any children.

g.title: j2999074295
g.text: I don't like to presume to understand things that are basically *gods.* This thing is trying to understand emotions. It's just doing a bad job of playing with its toys.

g.title: j2574391865
g.text: Just let it try to get between us. So help me Sol, I’ll end it. I’ll find a way.

g.title: j2304665323
g.text: Admirable theory, but we don't KNOW that, do we?

g.title: j2953441434
g.text: There are powers in the Universe that thing can’t stand against. I choose to believe it with every atom of myself.

g.title: j3959083243
g.text: If you're right, then it's blameless. Childlike, almost. That doesn't fit with what we know. It's malevolent.

g.title: j1233847847
g.text: If it swallows me whole I’ll stick in its throat and choke it.

g.title: j3062971920
g.text: That's a great way to die.

g.title: j3448685497
g.text: I don’t know how we’re going to do it yet, but I’m with you. We have to win.

g.title: j1302008358
g.text: I'm dead anyway in this scenario.

g.title: j1403686698
g.text: If this was a story, you’d come up with some clever trick. You’d dig up the giant’s stone heart and crack it with a swan’s feather, or trick it into throwing itself over a cliff.

g.title: j3615588470
g.text: But at least I get to spit in its eye.

g.title: j2819646129
g.text: You said you were a ‘journalist’. Those aren’t the sorts of stories you used to tell, are they? You told the truth, no matter how ugly it was.

g.title: j2188080053
g.text: If those old stories didn’t tell the truth, people wouldn’t have kept telling them.

g.title: j2550781257
g.text: I don’t mean giants are real. I just mean the old stories tell a different kind of truth.

g.title: j52418017
g.text: We’re going to need more than fairy tales to get through this, no matter how inspiring they are.

g.title: j3838057530
g.text: I’ve lived in a kingdom made from stories. I know how powerful they can be.

g.title: j821551631
g.text: I know. I wish I had more than instinct to go on.

g.title: j3437931401
g.text: I think the one thing all those giant-killer stories have in common is this: they’re all about learning the rules and figuring out how to be clever with them.

g.title: j4262940061
g.text: We're confronting something vast, terrifying and outside our comprehension. Normally only children get to do that. That's why fairy tales exist.

g.title: j4060845350
g.text: Some monsters are stupid. Some are compelled to be literal. Some have secrets. But you can’t win until you know the rules the monster’s bound by.

g.title: j853490642
g.text: It’s stuck in the Wall. I’m not even sure what the Wall is.

g.title: j1283251619
g.text: I don’t think the Indifference is bound by any rules.

g.title: j3978305509
g.text: Doesn't matter. If it really is stuck, then we can deduce two things, can't we?

g.title: j1873696825
g.text: It has to be! Even Gods have rules! No matter how powerful the Indifference seems, it’s not a God.

g.title: j526421255
g.text: One, it can be trapped. Maybe even imprisoned.

g.title: j633761133
g.text: You beat Thrax. It doesn’t matter how many times you failed and ended up on your arse. You WON. Why shouldn’t you beat the Man in the Wall, too?

g.title: j215952262
g.text: +15 Chemistry

g.title: j559265343
g.text: When did you stop being frightened of it, Eleanor?

g.title: j2527086035
g.text: And two, it WANTS something. It wants to get out. If we know what it wants, we're already one step ahead of it.

g.title: j2511555673
g.text: I didn’t.

g.title: j2215057650
g.text: +20 Chemistry

g.title: j1917420136
g.text: I’m just more frightened of losing you, okay?
